==Assassination==
{{Main|Assassination of James A. Garfield}}
[[File:Garfield assassination engraving cropped.jpg|thumb|250px|left|An engraving. Garfield, in the foreground, has been shot, and a man is catching him. Panicking crowds throng around.|Garfield with J. G. Blaine<U+2014>shot by [[Charles Guiteau]]. Engraving from ''The Illustrated Newspaper'']]
On the morning of July 2, 1881, President Garfield was on his way to his alma mater, [[Williams College]], where he was scheduled to deliver a speech. Garfield was accompanied by James G. Blaine, Robert Todd Lincoln, and his two sons, James and Harry.<ref>The Lincoln Institute, ''Robert Todd Lincoln (1843<U+2013>1926)''</ref> As the President was walking through the Sixth Street Station of the [[Baltimore and Potomac Railroad]] in Washington at 9:30&nbsp;am, he was shot twice by an [[assassin]], [[Charles J. Guiteau]], a disgruntled federal office-seeker armed with a .44 caliber pistol. As Guiteau was being arrested after the shooting, he repeatedly said, "I am a Stalwart of the [[Stalwart (politics)|Stalwarts]]! I did it and I want to be arrested! [[Chester A. Arthur|Arthur]] is President now!"<ref>[[#Doyle-Swaney|Doyle-Swaney]] (1881), p. 61; The Baltimore and Potomac Railroad station was located on the southwest corner of present-day Sixth Street N.W. and Constitution Avenue in Washington, D.C.</ref> This very briefly led to unfounded suspicions that Arthur or his supporters had put Guiteau up to the crime.<ref>[[#Peskin|Peskin]] (1978), p.599.</ref> [[File:B&PStation1908.jpg|thumb|200px|alt=An ornate Victorian Gothic style building with a square tower|[[Baltimore & Potomac Railroad]] Passenger Terminal, Washington, DC (1873<U+2013>77, [[Wilson Brothers & Company]], architects, demolished 1908). U.S. President James A. Garfield was shot in this station on July 2, 1881.]]
Guiteau was upset over the rejection of his repeated attempts to be appointed as the United States [[Consulate general|consul]] in [[Paris]]&nbsp;<U+2013> a position for which he had no qualifications. He suffered from many delusions, including one that he had produced a speech (written but never delivered) which he was convinced was pivotal to Garfield's election, and another, that he was destined to be President himself.<ref>[[#Peskin|Peskin]] (1978), p.590.</ref>

Garfield exclaimed immediately after he was shot, "My God, what is this?"<ref name="EyeWitness">EyeWitness to History (1999), ''The Death Of President Garfield, 1881''</ref> One bullet grazed Garfield's arm; the second bullet was thought later to have possibly lodged in his spine but could not be found; scientists today speculate that the bullet was near his lung. [[Alexander Graham Bell]] specifically devised a [[metal detector]] to find the bullet, but the device's signal was distorted by the metal bed springs.<ref>[[#Peskin|Peskin]] (1978), p.598.</ref><ref>e.g. [[Bill Bryson]]: ''Made in America: an Informal History of the English Language in the United States'', Black Swan, 1998, p.102.</ref> Garfield became increasingly ill over a period of several weeks due to infection, which caused his heart to weaken. He remained bedridden in the White House with fever and extreme pain.

As the heat of summer became more oppressive for the stricken President, a Navy engineer, with the help of Simon Newcomb, installed in Garfield's room what may have been the world's first air conditioner. An air blower was installed over a chest containing 6 tons of ice, with the air then dried by conduction through a long iron box filled with cotton screens, and connected to the room's heat vent. This device was at times capable of reducing the air temperature to 20<U+00B0>F (11<U+00B0>C)<!-- Do not use {{convert}}, this is a relative temperature difference. --> below the outside temperature.<ref>[[#Peskin|Peskin]] (1978), p.601.</ref>

Sympathies for President Garfield poured out across the nation and the world. Condolences came from the [[Umberto I of Italy|King of Italy]] and the [[Rothschild family|Rothschilds]]. Democratic Kentucky governor [[Luke P. Blackburn]] ordered a day of "public fasting and prayer".<ref>New York Times (July 6, 1881), ''Condolence and Inquiry";New York Times (July 11, 1881), ''A Day Of Fasting And Prayer''</ref>

On September 6 the ailing President was moved to the [[Jersey Shore]] in the vain hope that the fresh air and quiet there might aid his recovery.<ref>[[#McCabe|McCabe]] (1881), p. 647; [[#Brown|Brown]] (1881), p. 240</ref> In a matter of hours, local residents put down a special [[branch line|rail spur]] for Garfield's train; some of the ties are now part of the [[Garfield Tea House]]. The beach cottage Garfield was taken to has been demolished.<ref>[[#Vowell|Vowell]] (2005), p. 185</ref>
[[File:James Garfield2 1882 Issue-5c.jpg|thumb|165px|alt=a brown postage stamp has a portrait of Garfield in an oval within a shield. A banner below reads "five cents U.S. postage"|<center>The first Garfield stamp<br>issue of 1882</center>]]

On Monday, September 19, 1881, at 10:20 P.M. President Garfield suffered and died from a massive [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] and a ruptured [[splenic artery]] [[aneurysm]], following [[blood poisoning]] and bronchial [[pneumonia]].<ref>Rutkow (2006), ''James A. Garfield'', p. 85; Brown (1881), p. 257</ref> Garfield's chief doctor, Dr. Doctor Willard Bliss, (who was a [[Doctor of Medicine]] but whose [[given name]] was also "Doctor"), had unsuccessfully attempted to revive the fading President with restorative medication.<ref>New York Times (July 9, 1881), ''How Dr. Bliss Got His Name''; Rutkow (2006), ''James A. Garfield'', p. 85; Baxter (1891), ''History of the city of Grand Rapids, Michigan'', p. 699; Lamb (1909), ''History of the Medical Society of the District of Columbia: 1817<U+2013>1909'', p. 227</ref> Mrs. Garfield, having leaned over Garfield, kissed his brows and exclaimed, "Oh! Why am I made to suffer this cruel wrong?" Garfield was pronounced dead at 10:35 P.M. by Dr. Bliss in the [[Elberon, New Jersey|Elberon]] section of [[Long Branch, New Jersey]]. Mrs. Garfield remained with her dead husband for over an hour until prompted to leave the room. The wounded President died exactly two months before his 50th birthday. During the 80 days between his shooting and death, his only official act was to sign an [[extradition]] paper. His final words: "My work is done."<ref name="EyeWitness"/><ref>[[#Peskin|Peskin]] (1978), p.606.</ref> Garfield was the first President to be survived by his mother.

[[File:Garfield's Doctors Consulting.jpg|thumb|left|240px|alt=Newspaper engraving of six men. Five are seated and one is standing.|Doctors discuss Garfield's wounds.]]
According to some historians and medical experts Garfield may have survived his wounds had the doctors attending him had at their disposal today's medical research, techniques, and equipment.<ref name="Schaffer">[[#Schaffer|Schaffer]] (July 25, 2006), ''A President Felled by an Assassin and 1880<U+2019>s Medical Care'', New York Times.</ref> Standard medical practice at the time dictated that priority be given to locating the path of the bullet. Several of his doctors inserted their [[Asepsis|unsterilized]] fingers into the wound to probe for the bullet, a common practice in the 1880s.<ref name="Schaffer" /> American doctors had not fully accepted the sterilization technique implemented by [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister|Joseph Lister]] during the 1860s. Historians agree that massive infection was a significant factor in President Garfield's demise.<ref name="Schaffer" /> Biographer Peskin stated that medical malpractice did not contribute to Garfield's death; the inevitable infection and blood poisoning that would ensue from a deep bullet wound resulted in multiple organ damage and spinal bone fragmentation.<ref>[[#Peskin|Peskin]] (1978), p.607.</ref>

Guiteau was formerly indicted on October 14, 1881 for the murder of the President. Although Guiteau's council argued the [[insanity defense]], due to his odd character, the jury found him guilty on January 5, 1882 and he was sentenced to death.  Guiteau may have had [[syphilis]], a disease that causes physiological mental impairment.  Guiteau was executed on June 30, 1882.<ref>[[#Johnson|Johnson]] (2001), pp.53-56</ref> Interestingly, he was also heard to brag that important men in Europe put him up to the task, and had promised to protect him if he were caught. <ref> Ellen Brown, Web of Debt. (2009)</ref>

==State funeral, monuments, legacy==
[[File:Garfield-casket.jpg|thumb|alt=A casket sits on a bier in this black and white photo|President Garfield's casket [[lying in state]] at the [[United States Capitol rotunda|Capitol Rotunda]]]]
[[File:Garfieldmarker.jpg|thumb||alt=rectangular stone memorial with an American flag on the left|President Garfield's death site, [[Long Branch, New Jersey]]]][[File:GarfieldMonument.jpg|thumb|alt=Victorian Gothic monument in brown stone. The first floor is square and the second is cylindrical with a conical roof.|220px|[[James A. Garfield Memorial|Garfield Monument]] at [[Lake View Cemetery (Cleveland)|Lake View Cemetery]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio]]]]
President Garfield's casket and face were viewed by 1,500 people in Long Branch before being loaded on the funeral car.<ref>Boston Evening Transcript (September 21, 1881), ''Funeral of President Garfield'', p. 1</ref> As Garfield's funeral train set out, first to the Capitol and then continuing on a final leg to Cleveland for the burial, the tracks were blanketed with flowers and houses were adorned with flags. More than 70,000 citizens, some waiting over three hours, passed by his coffin as his body lay in state in Washington; later, on September 25, 1881, in Cleveland, more than 150,000<U+2014>a number equal to the entire population of that city<U+2014>likewise paid their respects.<ref>[[#Peskin|Peskin]] (1978), pp.608<U+2013>609.</ref> Garfield's body was viewed in a specially made pavilion powered by electric lighting.  A wreath sent by [[Queen Victoria]] adorned Garfield's coffin.<ref>New York Time (September 25, 1881), ''Lying in State at Home''</ref>  His body was temporarily interred in a vault in Cleveland's Lake View Cemetery until his permanent memorial was made.<ref>The Ithaca Democrat (September 29, 1881), ''The Last Sad Rites''</ref>

In 1884, a monument to President Garfield was completed by sculptor Frank Happersberger and was placed on the grounds of the [[Conservatory of Flowers|San Francisco Conservatory of Flowers]]. On the  base of the Garfield statue is a figure holding a broken sword symbolizing Garfield's assassinantion.<ref>(June 23, 2004), ''President James A. Garfield Monument''</ref>

On May 18, 1887 the [[James A. Garfield Monument]], was dedicated in Washington.  The monument is a 9 foot bronze statue of Garfield mounted on a 16 foot Baroque style base, located on the U.S. Capitol grounds.  Three male figures, each 5 foot in height, are on the base representing Garfield's life stages as a scholar, soldier, and statesman.<ref>Smithsonian Institution, ''James Garfield Monument, (sculpture).''</ref>

In 1889, members of the California gold mining town [[Bodie, California|Bodie]], commemorated Garfield's life and death by inscribing his name on a [[cenotaph]] located in [[Miners Union Cemetery]] in Bodie. The monument had initially been made to honor [[W. S. Bodey]], founder of the town, however, the community decided to commemorate the memorial to Garfield.<ref>Decloedt (Oct 18, 2001), ''James A. Garfield''; Woodbury (2002-2004), ''A visit to Bodie, Calif., the West's best ghost town''</ref>

On May 19, 1890, Garfield's body was permanently interred, with great solemnity and fanfare, in a [[mausoleum]] in [[Lake View Cemetery]] in Cleveland . Attending the "impressive" dedication ceremonies were former Presdient Rutherford B. Hayes, then current President Benjamin Harrison, and future President William McKinley.  Garfield's former Sec. Windom also attended the ceremony.  President Harrison stated that Garfield was always a "student and instructor" and that his life works and death would "continue to be instructive and inspiring incidents in American history".<ref>New York Times (March 30, 1890), ''The Garfield Memorial''</ref> Five panels on the monument display Garfield as a teacher, Union Major General, an [[orator]], taking the Presidential oath, and his body laying in state at the Capitol rotunda in Washington D.C.<ref>Lake View Cemetary, ''James A. Garfield Monument''</ref> 

The U.S. has twice had three presidents in the same year. The first such year was 1841. [[Martin Van Buren]] ended his single term, [[William Henry Harrison]] was inaugurated and died a month later, then Vice President [[John Tyler]] stepped into the vacant office. The second occurrence was in 1881. [[Rutherford B. Hayes]] relinquished the office to James A. Garfield. Upon Garfield's death, [[Chester A. Arthur]] became president.<ref>[[#Kelly|Kelly]] (June 9, 2008)</ref>

President Garfield's murder by a deranged federal office seeker awakened public awareness and prompted Congress to pass civil service reform legislation. Senator [[George H. Pendleton]], a Democrat from Ohio, launched a reform effort that resulted in President Chester A. Arthur signing into law the [[Pendleton Act]] in January 1883. This act reversed the "spoils system" where office seekers paid or gave political service in order to obtain or keep federally appointed positions. Under the Pendleton Act, office appointments were awarded on merit and competitive examination. The law made illegal the long-time practice of giving money or service to obtain a federal appointment. To ensure the reform was implemented, Congress and President Arthur established and funded the [[Civil Service Commission]]. The Pendleton Act, however, only covered 10% of federal government workers. President Arthur, who was previously known for having been a "veteran spoilsman", became an avid civil service reformer after President Garfield's assassination.<ref>Our Documents, ''Pendleton Act (1883)''; [[#Brogan|Brogan (1985)]], p. 419</ref>

Garfield's stress on the importance of education for [[African Americans]] served as a catalyst for their advancement.  As a scholar president, pre-dating [[Woodrow Wilson]], Garfield was an avid reader having a 3,000-book library that included Horace, Shakespeare, Goethe, Tennyson, and Froude's history of England.<ref>[[#Doenecke|Doenecke]] (1981), pp. 23, 182, 183</ref>
 
[[File:garfieldlifeinsurancepolicyback.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A hand written document|Surrender page of $10,000 [[life insurance]] policy]]
On January 12, 2010, a previously unknown life insurance policy on the life of Garfield was discovered in Orient, New York. The policy was found in a family scrapbook dating from the same period of his death and had a benefit amount of $10,000. It was opened on May 18, 1881, just 45 days prior to the date Garfield was shot by Guiteau, and was surrendered and signed by Lucretia Garfield and Joseph Stanley-Brown, both witnesses to Garfield's death.<ref>I've Got Neat Stuff, ''Garfield Life Insurance Policy Discovered''</ref>

A sandstone statue of Garfield was dedicated in May 2009 on the campus of [[Hiram College]]. A week later, the statue was [[decapitation|decapitated]] by vandals.<ref>Associated Press (May 18, 2009) , ''Statue of Former President Loses Head in Ohio''</ref>

All deceased U.S. presidents are represented on American postage stamps, but James Garfield is one of only a few [[US Presidents on US postage stamps|who have appeared]] more than twice. The first stamp issue to depict Garfield was a [[:File:James Garfield2 1882 Issue-5c.jpg|''memorial issue'']] released in Garfield's memory on April 10, 1882,  just seven months after his death.<ref>Smithsonian National Postal Museum, ''5-cent Garfield''.</ref> {{clear}}

